bib_record.title: Systematic study of the photodisintegration of Ge-70, Ge-72, Ge-74, and Ge-76.

free_txt: Cross  sections   were   obtained  from  the
method developed by Cook.  For yield curves obtained
from direct neutron detection  the  multiplicity-bin
analysis  of  the neutron counts for each individual
beam burst allowed the statistical extraction of the
reaction  multiplicities.  The  form of the spectrum
and the reaction rates  were  calculated  using  the
estimates for the  reaction  rates  were  calculated
using  statistical goryachev's method.  The reaction
rates were divided by beam monitor response to  form
uncorrected  yields.  The  final (or reduced) yields
were   calculated   by   the   application   of   an
energy-dependent  correction for the response of the
beam monitor to the bremsstrahlung beam.  For  yield
measurements  raw data were recorded  as a series of
g-ray  spectra  containing peaks from all activities
of interest,  a computer code was devised to  locate
desired  peaks,  obtain  the area of each peak,  and
correct for the response of the  beam  monitor.  The
area  of  each  peak  was  calculated  by  numerical
integration after fitting and substracting  off  the
background spectrum. these areas were divided by the
beam monitor response to form the reduced yields.
The corrections  were  made  for  the response of the
beam monitor to the bremsstrahlung beam.
Cross sections  for  the (g,n),  the (g,2n),  and the
(g,np) reactions for Ge-70, Ge-72, Ge-74, and Ge-76,
and  the (g,p) reaction for Ge-74 have been measured
from  threshold  to  40  MeV  at  the   Iowa   State
results were obtained  by  unfolding  bremsstrahlung
section was obtained for each isotope by adding  the
partial  cross  sections  together.  Cross  sections
integrated to 40 MeV are given to each reaction.

Separated isotopes of germanium were obtained in form
of GeO. In order to avoid contamination of the yield
data with the effects of oxygen resonances,  the GeO
samples were  reduced  to  metallic  germanium.  The
targets  were  fabricated  into  wafers  with a beam
interception area of about  1.5  cm**2  and  average
weight of 0.98 g. The isotopic purity of each sample
